A **Business Case** in Workplace 2 is a structured workflow that guides you through customer communication tasks, such as opening a service contract or processing a support request efficiently and accurately. Workplace 2 provides a clear and uncluttered interface for completing Business Cases and monitoring the overall status of the workflow, as well as its individual steps.

This guide will walk you through each step of a typical Business Case, from selecting a template to sending the final document to the customer. In this scenario, you will draw up a bank service contract and preview the document in PDF format. Finally, you send the finished contract via email to the end customer.

The entire process consists of the following steps:

- **Start the Business Case**

- **Select a document template**

- **Customize the document template** in Composer

- **Preview the document as PDF**

- **Send the PDF via email**

- **Complete the Business Case**

> Tip: Use the provided example Business Case

You can use the attached Business Case files to follow this guide in your Workplace 2 application. Ask your Workplace 2 administrator to upload the Business Case definition and activate it for you.

## Before you begin
You must have at least the following rights to open the example Business Case:

- **Access to Workplace 2** (login required)

- **Access to Composer** (login required)

- **User rights to start Business Cases**

- **User rights to open and edit Human Tasks**

> User access restrictions

Business Cases and Human Tasks are highly customizable. Certain Business Cases or individual Human Tasks may require specific user rights to open or edit, depending on their configuration, and may therefore not be visible to you.

The Business Case used in this walkthrough doesnâ€™t have any user access restrictions. Contact your Workplace 2 administrator if you are missing any of the above requirements or have trouble opening the example Business Case.

## Start the Business Case
To start the workflow, log into Workplace 2. After authenticating, you will be directed to the **Dashboard** landing page.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Open Workplace 2 and navigate to the **Business Cases** tab.

- Select the example Business Case and click **Start**.

- If you canâ€™t find the example Business Case, use the **global search bar** at the top to find it by name or Business Case ID.

In the background, the Business Case definition will be instantiated and a unique Business Case Instance created from it. On your screen, the **task editor** will be opened automatically, and you will see the first step in the workflow.

## Step 1: Select a document template
The first step in the workflow is a **File List Human Task**. This task requires the user to select one or more document templates from a predefined selection. In this example, you can choose from different language versions of the same service contract template.

![File selection interface showing English and German templates for Doxee Bank.](data:image/png;base64,)

- Select one of the available document templates by clicking its checkbox.

- Click **Continue** in the left navigation bar.

The progress indicator in the left sidebar will move to the next step in the workflow, and its content will open in the large editing area.

## Step 2: Customize the document template in Composer
In the next step, a **Composer Human Task**, the service contract template is opened in Composer. The application may auto-fill some variable data fields, like names and addresses, from your CRM system.

> Composer

Composer is a separate Doxee application. To find out more about its features and functions, please refer to its [product documentation](/doxee-platform/docs/composer).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Customize the service contract, for example by selecting a consultant and subscription plan in the Insertion Points tab (Composer feature).

- Sign the service contract in the Signature field (Composer feature).

- Click **Continue** in the left navigation bar.

The progress indicator in the left sidebar will move to the next step in the workflow, and its content will open in the large editing area.

## Step 3: Preview the contract as PDF
After the contract template has been customized with Composer, you can preview it in PDF format with **PDF Preview Human Task** to check whether everything is correct.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Review the rendered PDF document of the service contract.

- Click **Continue** in the left navigation bar.

The progress indicator in the left sidebar will move to the next step in the workflow, and its content will open in the large editing area.

## Step 4: Send the PDF via email
The final step in the workflow is an **Email Human Task**. It sends an email with the signed contract to the customer. The application may pre-fill some fields, like email address and default subject line, based on CRM data and the configuration of the task.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Fill the required fields in the email form interface (marked with an asterisk). The service contract PDF will be automatically attached to the email.

- Click **Continue **in the left navigation bar.

The progress indicator in the left sidebar will mark this step in the workflow as completed, and the large editing area will display a confirmation message that the Business Case has been successfully completed.

## Complete the Business Case
Congrats! Youâ€™ve just successfully completed your first Business Case.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

You can exit the task editor by going to one of the suggested tabs (**Business Cases** or **Tabs**), or by clicking the Workplace 2 icon in the top left corner; this will redirect you to back to the **Dashboard**.

Business Cases are interactive processes which are started and completed from Workplace. A Business Case typically consists of one or several Human Tasks, which require user input in order to advance the process. An open Business Case is called a Business Case Instance.

Composer is a web-based application for editing document templates which were created with Business Designer. It is used mainly to resolve dynamic fields into real data read from a database.
